    "excerpt": "The legends who created this music are now in their 80s — or gone. Arena tickets cost a fortune. There has never been a better moment to hear these songs played live, up close, and done right.",
    "body": "Here's an uncomfortable truth for fans of '60s music: the window to see the original artists is closing fast.\n\nThe musicians who created the British Invasion are now in their late 70s and 80s. Some have retired from the road. Many are no longer with us. The few legacy acts still touring are doing farewell runs — and charging accordingly.\n\nThat's exactly why this era of live music belongs to the shows that keep the songs alive *properly*. Not karaoke. Not a wedding-band medley. A full, researched, note-for-note recreation performed by career musicians who grew up on this material and treat it with the respect it deserves.\n\n**Three things have lined up at once:**\n\nThe originals are aging out. The catalog is too important to disappear from the stage. And audiences are rediscovering how much better this music feels live than it ever could through a speaker.\n\nThat's the whole reason The British Invasion Years exists. We're not trying to replace your memory of seeing the Stones in 1972 — we're trying to give you a night where the music sounds *that alive* again, in a room small enough that you can actually feel it.\n\nThe songs aren't getting any younger. Neither are any of us. Find a [show near you](tour.html) and don't wait on it.",
