    "excerpt": "Sixty years after its release, The Beatles' Revolver remains arguably the most innovative rock album ever made. Here's why it still sounds like the future.",
    "body": "In August 1966, The Beatles released *Revolver* — and nothing in popular music was ever quite the same again.\n\nAt a moment when most rock bands were still playing relatively straightforward arrangements, The Beatles made an album that was genuinely avant-garde: string quartets on \"Eleanor Rigby,\" backwards guitar solos on \"I'm Only Sleeping,\" psychedelic studio manipulation on \"Tomorrow Never Knows,\" the warm Motown-influenced bounce of \"Got to Get You into My Life.\"\n\nSixty years on, *Revolver* holds up not just as a great album but as arguably the most creatively ambitious rock record ever made. It points forward to everything that came after — psychedelia, art rock, ambient music, sampling — while sounding completely of its moment.\n\nFor The British Invasion Years, albums like *Revolver* are both inspiration and standard. The craftsmanship, the attention to arrangement, the commitment to doing something *interesting* with every song — that's the bar the '60s set, and it's the bar we hold ourselves to on stage.\n\nCome experience the music live. Some songs just need to be heard with a crowd.",
