    "excerpt": "The Beatles. The Rolling Stones. The Kinks. The Who. The Animals. Everyone has a favorite — and everyone has a story about why the '60s changed their musical life.",
    "body": "Ask a room full of '60s music fans to name their favorite British Invasion band and you'll start a conversation that doesn't end for hours. It's one of the great debates in music history — and there's no wrong answer.\n\n**Team Beatles?** The songwriting depth, the evolution from *Please Please Me* to *Abbey Road*, the sheer number of eras within a single decade. Hard to argue against them.\n\n**Team Stones?** The raw blues swagger, the longevity, the undeniable cool. Keith Richards' riffs are literally part of the DNA of rock and roll.\n\n**Team Kinks?** Often underrated, endlessly influential. Ray Davies was writing social commentary disguised as pop songs while everyone else was writing about holding hands.\n\n**Team Who?** Pure explosive energy. Pete Townshend's windmill. Keith Moon. *My Generation.* Enough said.\n\nAt a British Invasion Years show, you don't have to choose — you get all of them, plus the American acts that rose to meet the moment. The '60s were a golden era precisely because of the competition, the creativity, and the incredible volume of great music being made simultaneously.\n\nWhat's your favorite? Come see us live and let the music answer for you.",
    "featured": false,
    "image": "images/home/band-onstage-peace-sign-backdrop.jpg"
